      <hedline>
        <hl1>Class Warfare and the Great Unmentionable</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>John E Hofmann letter disputes Bob Herbert's August 21 Op-Ed column on presidential campaign of Vice Pres Al Gore</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''This Is Class Warfare?'', by Bob Herbert (column, Aug. 21):</p>
        <p>Mr. Herbert wants us to believe that Al Gore is not engaged in class warfare. What Mr. Herbert doesn't mention, and what Mr. Gore refuses to acknowledge, is where the surplus comes from in the first place.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''This Is Class Warfare?'', by Bob Herbert (column, Aug. 21):</p>
        <p>Mr. Herbert wants us to believe that Al Gore is not engaged in class warfare. What Mr. Herbert doesn't mention, and what Mr. Gore refuses to acknowledge, is where the surplus comes from in the first place.</p>
        <p>Most of the government revenue, and hence the surplus, comes from taxes. And who pays most of the taxes? The very rich, who are accused of being greedy for wanting some of this back.</p>
        <p>The government already transfers huge sums of money from the rich to the poor. Apparently, Mr. Herbert believes that the surplus belongs not to the people who financed it but to the government to distribute as Al Gore sees fit.</p>
        <p>JOHN E. HOFMANN  Brewster, Mass., Aug. 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
